Prerequisites for each rhel OS

Below are the minimum hardware requirements for recent major releases on x86_64 architecture.


Network installation (HTTP/HTTPS/FTP) typically requires more RAM because the installer must load images into memory.

RHEL 7 
Minimum RAM	1 GB
Recommended RAM	2 GB+
Minimum Disk	10 GB
Processor	64-bit x86_64
Network RAM*	N/A

RHEL 8
Minimum RAM	1.5 GiB (Local/NFS)
Recommended RAM	2 GB - 8 GB+
Minimum Disk	10 GB
Processor	64-bit x86_64
Network RAM*  3 GiB (HTTP/FTP)

RHEL 9
Minimum RAM		2 GB (4 GB recommended)
Recommended RAM		4 GB - 16 GB+
Minimum Disk	10 GB (20 GB recommended)
Processor	x86-64-v2 microarchitecture
Network RAM*	3.5 GiB (HTTP/FTP)

Key Version-Specific Prerequisites
RHEL 9:
CPU: Requires the x86-64-v2 microarchitecture level or later (CPUs from roughly 2009 onwards, like Intel Nehalem or AMD Bulldozer).
Support: Designed for modern workloads with a focus on hybrid cloud and containerization.
RHEL 8:
Architecture: Supports x86_64, aarch64 (ARM), ppc64le (IBM Power), and s390x (IBM Z).
RAM: While 1.5 GiB is the minimum for local media, 2 GB is recommended for standard production workloads.
RHEL 7:
End of Life: This version reached its end-of-life in 2024, meaning it no longer receives standard security updates.
Low-End: Can run on older 64-bit hardware that may not meet the x86-64-v2 requirement of RHEL 9.

Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) 8 Installation Steps with Screenshots

Red Hat has released its most awaited OS RHEL 8 on 7th May 2019. RHEL 8 is based on Fedora 28 distribution and Linux kernel version 4.18.  One of the important key features in RHEL 8 is that it has introduced “Application Streams” which allows developers tools, frameworks and languages to be updated frequently without impacting the core resources of base OS. In other words, application streams will help to segregate the users space packages from OS Kernel Space.

Apart from this, there are many new features which are noticed in RHEL 8 like:

XFS File system supports copy-on-write of file extents
Introduction of Stratis filesystem, Buildah, Podman, and Skopeo
Yum utility is based on DNF
Chrony replace NTP.
Cockpit is the default Web Console tool for Server management.
OpenSSL 1.1.1 & TLS 1.3 support
PHP 7.2
iptables replaced by nftables
Minimum System Requirements for RHEL 8:
4 GB RAM
20 GB unallocated disk space
64-bit x86 or ARM System
Note: RHEL 8 supports the following architectures:

AMD or Intel x86 64-bit
64-bit ARM
IBM Power Systems, Little Endian & IBM Z

2. Installation Steps
Boot from Media: Boot your system using a USB or DVD containing the RHEL 8 ISO. Select "Install Red Hat Enterprise Linux 8.x" from the boot menu.

Localization: Select your preferred language and keyboard layout.

Installation Destination: Click Installation Destination to select your disk. You can use Automatic partitioning (creates LVM volumes and XFS filesystem) or Custom if you need specific mount points.

Network & Hostname: Select Network & Host Name, toggle the Ethernet adapter to ON, and optionally set a custom hostname.

Software Selection: Choose a Base Environment (e.g., "Server with GUI", "Server", or "Workstation"). You can also select additional software add-ons here.

User Settings: Set a strong Root Password and create a Local User. It is recommended to check "Make this user administrator" to allow the use of sudo.

Begin Installation: Click Begin Installation. Once finished, click Reboot and remove the installation media.


